System instructions
System instructions set persistent context for all messages.
Example LangGraph node function:
def respond(state: State) -&gt; dict:
    response = client.models.generate_content(
        model="gemini-3-flash-preview",
        contents=[state["prompt"]],
        config=types.GenerateContentConfig(
            system_instruction="You are a helpful coding assistant...",
            temperature=0.7,
        ),
    )
    return {"response": response.text}

Structured outputs: response_schema
Example LangGraph node function with guaranteed JSON:
def analyze_review(state: State) -&gt; dict:
    response = client.models.generate_content(
        model="gemini-3-flash-preview",
        contents=[state["review"]],
        config=types.GenerateContentConfig(
            system_instruction="Extract sentiment, key points, and rating guess.",
            response_mime_type="application/json",
            response_schema={
                "type": "object",
                "properties": {
                    "sentiment": {
                        "type": "string",
                        "enum": ["positive", "negative", "neutral"]
                    },
                    "key_points": {
                        "type": "array",
                        "items": {"type": "string"},
                        "maxItems": 3
                    },
                    "rating_guess": {"type": "integer", "minimum": 1, "maximum": 5}
                }
            }
        ),
    )
    return {"analysis": json.loads(response.text)}
response_mime_type: "application/json", "text/x.enum", or "text/plain" (default)

Prompt chaining: state and nodes
Break complex tasks into steps. Define state and node functions:
class State(TypedDict):
    article: str
    summary: str
    points: str
    questions: str

def summarize(state: State) -&gt; dict:
    response = client.models.generate_content(
        model="gemini-3-flash-preview",
        contents=[f"Summarize this article: {state['article']}"]
    )
    return {"summary": response.text}

def extract_points(state: State) -&gt; dict:
    response = client.models.generate_content(
        model="gemini-3-flash-preview",
        contents=[f"List 3 key points from: {state['summary']}"]
    )
    return {"points": response.text}

def generate_questions(state: State) -&gt; dict:
    response = client.models.generate_content(
        model="gemini-3-flash-preview",
        contents=[f"Create quiz questions about: {state['points']}"]
    )
    return {"questions": response.text}

Python: if you know another language
Python will feel familiar. Key differences:

Indentation matters — blocks are defined by whitespace, not braces
Dynamic typing — no type declarations required (but type hints are optional)
Everything is an object — functions, classes, modules

def greet(name):
    if name:
        return f"Hello, {name}!"
    else:
        return "Hello, stranger!"
